Soviet Jewish response to World War II and the Nazi destruction of the Jews, disputing the claim that Jews in Soviet Russia did not and could not react to the killings of Jews. It reveals a largely unknown body of Jewish literature beginning as early as 1942 that responds to the mass killings. By exploring works through the early twenty-first century, the book reveals a complex, emotionally rich, and intensely vibrant Soviet Jewish culture that persisted beyond Stalinist oppression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aRussian literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aYiddish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aYiddish literaturezSoviet UnionxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804779043zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804779043.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles